- Discussion regarding Chapter 133, Fenton Tree Advisory Board, of the Municipal Code. A copy of the Ordinance approved by the Board of Aldermen on June 22, 2023, that establishes Chapter 133, Fenton Tree Advisory Board, of the Municipal Code was available for review.

It was suggested that the Board consider the adoption of a Tree Advisory Board Ordinance to qualify as a "Tree City USA" under the Arbor Day Foundation. Although adoption of the Ordinance was not required in the past by the Arbor Day Foundation, an Ordinance is now recommended (and will most likely be required in the near future) that the City have a Tree Ordinance to meet the Tree City USA requirements.

Benefits of being a Tree City include additional grant funding through the Missouri Department of Conservation (specifically the Community Forestry Cost-Share Program) at a 75%/25% cost share in lieu of a 50%/50% cost share.

Mike Abbott inquired if a copy of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) A300 would be available for review. City Administrator Nikki Finkbiner replied a copy would be obtained.

Chairman Gary Johnson inquired if trees located in subdivision entrance islands were included. City Administrator Nikki Finkbiner replied no, they are private not public area.

Per Section 133.040(E) the duties of the Tree Advisory Board include:

1. Coordinate and promote Arbor Day activities;
2. Review and update a five-year plan to plant and maintain Public Trees;
3. Support public awareness and education programs relating to trees;
4. Review City Department concerns relating to tree care;
5. Submit an annual report of its activities to the Board of Aldermen;
6. Assist with the annual application to renew the Tree City USA designation;
7. Recommend a list of tree species for planting on Public Property, and a list of prohibited species; and
8. Other duties that may be assigned by the Board of Aldermen.

Per Section 133.040(F) the Advisory Tree Board shall meet a minimum of four (4) times each year. It was noted that going forward the Parks and Recreation Committee agenda will include the Advisory Tree Board.

